<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About This Union Territory</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Portugal's <em>Last Footprint in India</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Dadra & Nagar Haveli and Daman & Diu — merged into a single Union Territory on January 26, 2020 — represents the last, most scattered and perhaps the most surprising chapter of European colonialism in India. While the British and French held their Indian territories until 1947 and 1954 respectively, the Portuguese clung to their small coastal enclaves until 1961, when the Indian Army's Operation Vijay ended 451 years of Portuguese rule in a swift 36-hour military action. The combined UT comprises four distinct geographical units spread along India's western coast: Daman — a small port town on the Gujarat coast with a walled old city, a magnificent 16th-century Portuguese fort and a seafront promenade; Diu — a luminous limestone island off the southern tip of the Kathiawar Peninsula, blessed with extraordinary Portuguese architecture, clear beaches and a silence that Goa lost decades ago; Dadra & Nagar Haveli — an inland enclave surrounded entirely by Gujarat and Maharashtra, covered in dense tribal forest and home to the Varli, Kokaná, Dhodia and Naikda tribes whose ancient culture predates the Portuguese arrival by millennia. The Portuguese presence — concentrated in Daman and Diu — left behind architecture of enduring quality: the Moti Daman Fort (the finest Portuguese fortification in India), the St. Paul's Church (Diu, whose baroque facade rivals anything in Goa), the Church of Bom Jesus (Daman) and dozens of smaller colonial buildings whose yellow-ochre plaster and terracotta roof tiles create a Mediterranean atmosphere on the Arabian Sea coast. Today Daman and Diu are among India's most relaxed holiday destinations — less crowded than Goa, more authentic, with excellent beaches, seafood and the peaceful rhythm of small coastal towns that haven't yet been overwhelmed by mass tourism.</p>

  <div class="merger-note">
    <strong>📋 Administrative Note:</strong> This Union Territory was formed on <strong>January 26, 2020</strong> by merging the previously separate UTs of Dadra & Nagar Haveli and Daman & Diu. The capital is <strong>Daman</strong>. The UT has 3 districts: Daman, Diu, and Dadra & Nagar Haveli. Total area: 603 sq km. Total population: approximately 586,000.
  </div>
</section>

